An easy way to have an automated continuous view of the compiled pdf is to have a second buffer with auto-revert-mode. Thus, whenever running C-c C-c LaTeX <RET> the pdf will be recompiled automatically. You can also add this action to the save hook.

  (add-hook 'LaTeX-mode-hook
            (lambda ()
              (add-hook 'after-save-hook
                        (lambda ()
                          (TeX-command "LaTeX" 'TeX-master-file -1)
                          ) nil 'local)))

-- Kevin 2017-04-27 02:37 UTC


----

I just use [http://mg.readthedocs.io/latexmk.html latexmk], which will keep recompiling automatically, and I use a PDF viewer that automatically reloads the file if it changes, e.g. [http://skim-app.sourceforge.net/ Skim].

{{{
;; limit to the commands I need
(setq tex-compile-commands
      '(("latexmk -pvc -view=none -bibtex- -pdf %f" t "%r.pdf")
	("skim $f")
	("pdflatex  %f" t "%r.pdf")
	("makeindex %r" "%r.idx" "%r.ind")))
}}}

-- Alex Schroeder 2017-04-30 01:09 UTC

